WEBVTT

00:01.627 --> 00:04.087
DOTTIE:
What are you
going to do about this?

00:04.087 --> 00:06.632
I know what I'm not
going to do, and that's panic.

00:06.632 --> 00:07.716
Abigail's right.

00:07.716 --> 00:08.801
I've seen banks fail,

00:08.801 --> 00:10.260
and it's fear in the community

00:10.260 --> 00:11.804
that pushes them
over the edge.

00:11.804 --> 00:14.306
The bank's got our money,
and it's already closed.

00:14.306 --> 00:15.808
Have they
lost it all?

00:15.808 --> 00:17.309
I understand
you're worried--

00:17.309 --> 00:19.561
I just want my money.
I need to buy supplies.

00:19.561 --> 00:21.271
What are we supposed to do?

00:21.271 --> 00:22.523
I will deal with this,

00:22.523 --> 00:24.525
but I promise you
the bank will re-open.

00:24.525 --> 00:27.486
WOMAN: When?
[SIGHS] Soon.

00:27.486 --> 00:29.697
I-I--
Just give me some time.

00:29.697 --> 00:32.240
How much time?
I don't know. Days.

00:32.240 --> 00:33.659
Maybe a couple of weeks?

00:33.659 --> 00:35.703
[TOWNSFOLK MURMURING]

00:35.703 --> 00:38.288
You can trust Abigail!
We're all in this together.

00:38.288 --> 00:40.123
Jack's right.
We need to give Abigail

00:40.123 --> 00:41.458
a little bit of time
to work this out.

00:41.458 --> 00:43.502
Thank you, Lee.
Until then,

00:43.502 --> 00:45.671
everyone go about
your normal business.

00:47.006 --> 00:49.174
Goodness.
How are we supposed to do that?

00:49.174 --> 00:50.801
I need a cup of tea.

00:50.801 --> 00:53.679
Can I talk to you
in my office?

00:59.142 --> 01:01.937
[SIGHS]

01:05.566 --> 01:08.944
What's your plan?

01:08.944 --> 01:10.738
I don't know.

01:10.738 --> 01:12.239
[SIGHS]

01:12.239 --> 01:15.701
Jenkins tried to get a loan
to keep the bank afloat.

01:15.701 --> 01:17.703
Obviously,
that didn't happen.

01:17.703 --> 01:21.040
They must not see him
as a good credit risk.

01:21.040 --> 01:23.166
Bill, what am I
going to do?

01:23.166 --> 01:25.711
You're gonna stay patient,
work this thing out.

01:25.711 --> 01:28.255
Until then, you did
the best thing a leader can do--

01:28.255 --> 01:30.382
you kept people
from panicking.

01:30.382 --> 01:32.760
Well, at best,
I bought a little time.

01:32.760 --> 01:35.679
Yeah, which is exactly
what we need right now.

01:35.679 --> 01:38.181
Time for cooler heads
to prevail.

01:45.898 --> 01:48.525
Jack.
I was talking to Rosemary.

01:48.525 --> 01:50.819
I turned around, you were gone.
JACK: Oh, sorry.

01:50.819 --> 01:53.739
Once Rosemary is talking, I
never know when it's gonna end.

01:53.739 --> 01:56.116
That's true.
What are you doing?

01:56.116 --> 01:57.701
I got to head out
to do something

01:57.701 --> 02:00.454
I should've done long ago.
Which is?

02:00.454 --> 02:04.541
I want it to be a surprise...
but it'll make you happy.

02:04.541 --> 02:05.793
Hm...

02:05.793 --> 02:07.962
All right.

02:07.962 --> 02:09.713
When will you be back?

02:10.881 --> 02:12.049
Soon.

02:13.133 --> 02:15.677
Day after tomorrow.

02:15.677 --> 02:17.846
Are you okay?

02:17.846 --> 02:20.348
Yeah. Absolutely. Why?

02:20.348 --> 02:22.476
I asked you about
the Northern Territories,

02:22.476 --> 02:24.519
and you didn't want
to talk about it,

02:24.519 --> 02:26.105
and now this...

02:26.105 --> 02:28.857
There's not much to say
about the Northern Territories.

02:28.857 --> 02:31.359
And this is a surprise.

02:31.359 --> 02:32.903
Trust me.

02:34.071 --> 02:35.489
[SIGHS]

02:35.489 --> 02:37.491
Safe travels.

02:37.491 --> 02:39.367
See you soon.

02:39.367 --> 02:42.203
[♪♪♪]

02:42.203 --> 02:44.832
[DOOR OPENS, THEN SHUTS]

02:48.209 --> 02:50.420
[♪♪♪]

03:13.192 --> 03:14.736
ROSEMARY:
Just think--

03:14.736 --> 03:16.113
in a little over a week,

03:16.113 --> 03:18.907
you're going to be
"Mrs. Jack Thornton".

03:18.907 --> 03:20.534
Oh, it's so exciting.

03:20.534 --> 03:23.286
I know! I can
hardly believe it.

03:23.286 --> 03:25.956
I just wish I knew
why Jack had to leave town

03:25.956 --> 03:27.499
on this mystery
mission of his.

03:27.499 --> 03:30.251
Maybe he's buying you
a wedding present.

03:30.251 --> 03:31.461
A gold broach. Oh!

03:31.461 --> 03:33.421
Or diamond earrings.

03:33.421 --> 03:35.632
Jack knows he doesn't
have to prove his love

03:35.632 --> 03:36.967
with expensive gifts.

03:36.967 --> 03:38.468
Jewelry never hurt.

03:38.468 --> 03:39.845
[SCOFFS]

03:39.845 --> 03:42.347
You're really
worried about him.

03:42.347 --> 03:44.725
Ever since Jack came home,

03:44.725 --> 03:46.060
I can't help but feel like

03:46.060 --> 03:47.895
he's holding
something back from me.

03:47.895 --> 03:49.396
He just isn't himself.

03:49.396 --> 03:52.024
You should mention that to him
when he gets home.

03:52.024 --> 03:54.359
ROSEMARY:
In the meantime...

03:54.359 --> 03:56.486
there are a lot
of preparations,

03:56.486 --> 03:58.197
and very little time
to do them.

03:58.197 --> 04:01.158
Elizabeth, I'll need you to meet
me at Dottie's after school.

04:01.158 --> 04:04.244
I will have the design
of the dress ready to show you.

04:04.244 --> 04:06.788
And Dottie, once
she picks up your fabric,

04:06.788 --> 04:08.916
Clara will set aside
everything else

04:08.916 --> 04:10.333
and start sewing.

04:10.333 --> 04:12.502
Now, Abigail.
You're coordinating

04:12.502 --> 04:14.671
the wedding dinner. Right?
That's right.

04:14.671 --> 04:17.007
We have to sit down
to discuss the menu,

04:17.007 --> 04:18.759
but I was thinking

04:18.759 --> 04:21.302
prime rib with
all the trimmings.

04:21.302 --> 04:23.931
Oh! That sounds delicious.

04:23.931 --> 04:25.348
Yes!

04:25.348 --> 04:27.935
But all this is going to cost
a lot of money,

04:27.935 --> 04:30.104
and everyone's so low
on funds right now.

04:30.104 --> 04:31.939
Maybe we shouldn't get
so carried away.

04:31.939 --> 04:34.524
ROSEMARY:
No! Sh-sh-sh!
Nonsense!

04:34.524 --> 04:38.237
You only get married once.

04:40.363 --> 04:42.616
She's right.

04:43.491 --> 04:45.660
[ALL CHUCKLE]

04:45.660 --> 04:49.123
ELIZABETH:
Ferdinand Magellan
was a Portuguese explorer

04:49.123 --> 04:52.417
who was the first European
to cross the Pacific Ocean.

04:52.417 --> 04:53.501
Any questions?

04:53.501 --> 04:54.711
Anna?

04:54.711 --> 04:57.005
Are we all invited
to the wedding?

04:57.005 --> 04:58.548
[ALL LAUGH]

04:58.548 --> 05:00.634
I meant questions
about explorers,

05:00.634 --> 05:02.552
but since you asked...

05:02.552 --> 05:05.055
Yes! Of course! You're all
invited to our wedding.

05:05.055 --> 05:06.974
STUDENTS:
Yay!

05:06.974 --> 05:08.642
Now, back to Magellan--

05:08.642 --> 05:09.935
Can I be an usher?

05:09.935 --> 05:11.228
Can I be the flower girl?

05:11.228 --> 05:13.772
[ALL CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

05:13.772 --> 05:16.691
Oh! All right, all right!
Listen, listen!

05:16.691 --> 05:18.902
I promise, you're all
invited to the wedding,

05:18.902 --> 05:22.572
and each and every one of you
will have a very special job.

05:22.572 --> 05:25.242
You all mean so much
to Mountie Jack and me,

05:25.242 --> 05:28.203
and we're very glad you'll
be there to help us celebrate.

05:28.203 --> 05:31.206
Okay. Time for recess.
Class dismissed!

05:31.206 --> 05:32.791
[COWBELL CLANGING]

05:33.708 --> 05:35.585
Miss Thatcher?
Yes, Philip?

05:35.585 --> 05:37.462
Thanks for inviting us
to your wedding.

05:37.462 --> 05:40.299
Oh, you're welcome.
I hope your dad can come too.

05:40.299 --> 05:41.842
If he gets home in time.

05:41.842 --> 05:45.220
He's been working out of town
for a while, hasn't he?

05:45.220 --> 05:48.723
At his new job...
but I hope he'll be home soon.

05:48.723 --> 05:51.726
So, what's my job gonna be
at the wedding?

05:51.726 --> 05:53.312
Oh...

05:53.312 --> 05:54.896
You know what?

05:54.896 --> 05:57.524
I have the perfect job for you.

05:57.524 --> 05:59.901
How would you like to be
our ring bearer?

05:59.901 --> 06:01.569
What does
the ring bearer do?

06:01.569 --> 06:03.280
He carries the rings
down the aisle.

06:03.280 --> 06:05.115
Nothing more important
than that?

06:05.115 --> 06:07.909
The person who carries them
has to be extra trustworthy.

06:07.909 --> 06:09.410
That sounds very important.

06:09.410 --> 06:11.830
It is.
Will you do it for us?

06:11.830 --> 06:15.000
Yes! Thanks, Miss Thatcher.

06:16.793 --> 06:19.921
[♪♪♪]

06:21.506 --> 06:23.008
[SIGHS]

06:26.011 --> 06:29.139
Sofia, could you hold up
the blue chiffon for me?

06:29.139 --> 06:31.016
Mm-hmm. Dark blue
or light blue?

06:31.016 --> 06:33.810
Oh. Let's go with
the light blue.

06:36.437 --> 06:37.731
Oh! No!

06:37.731 --> 06:39.900
No, no, no, no, no.
That won't do.

06:39.900 --> 06:41.484
Well, why not?

06:41.484 --> 06:43.153
When the sunlight
hits the fabric

06:43.153 --> 06:46.323
at just
a certain angle,

06:46.323 --> 06:48.909
it almost looks white.

06:48.909 --> 06:50.409
And we all know

06:50.409 --> 06:53.038
that nothing should compete
with the bride's dress.

06:53.038 --> 06:56.250
It's the centerpiece
of the entire celebration.

06:56.250 --> 06:58.252
People will be talking
about this dress

06:58.252 --> 07:00.045
for days, weeks...

07:00.045 --> 07:02.089
maybe even years to come.

07:02.089 --> 07:03.631
Mm! So...

07:03.631 --> 07:05.300
Hold up the dark blue, please.

07:08.427 --> 07:09.554
Ah!

07:09.554 --> 07:11.932
Perfect. Dark blue it is.

07:11.932 --> 07:14.101
These are
going to be beautiful.

07:14.101 --> 07:15.643
Mm. If I can
only finish

07:15.643 --> 07:17.478
these bridesmaids'
dresses on time,

07:17.478 --> 07:19.731
and, of course,
Elizabeth's dress.

07:19.731 --> 07:21.983
Good morning, Sofia.

07:21.983 --> 07:23.651
Ah. Good morning, Lee.

07:23.651 --> 07:25.695
Good morning,
my lovely wife.

07:25.695 --> 07:26.780
Any breakfast for me?

07:26.780 --> 07:27.822
Oh. Lee...

07:27.822 --> 07:29.324
I have so much
on my plate,

07:29.324 --> 07:30.992
I haven't had time
to fill yours.

07:30.992 --> 07:33.536
Oh, there's some bread
on the counter.

07:33.536 --> 07:35.747
Bread? Great.

07:35.747 --> 07:37.040
Bread.

07:42.296 --> 07:44.798
Henry.

07:44.798 --> 07:46.800
Can I talk to you
for a moment?

07:47.884 --> 07:50.720
Sure. But if Jesse Flynn
comes by,

07:50.720 --> 07:52.764
I got to get
back to work, though.

07:52.764 --> 07:54.391
Henry...

07:54.391 --> 07:56.393
I need your help
with the bank.

07:56.393 --> 07:57.685
I have to find investors,

07:57.685 --> 07:59.271
or the town is
in deep trouble.

07:59.271 --> 08:00.688
Look at me, Abigail.

08:00.688 --> 08:03.108
I gotta wash sawdust
out of my teeth every night.

08:03.108 --> 08:05.235
I don't know
that I can help you with that.

08:05.235 --> 08:07.237
You know people, Henry.
Important people.

08:07.237 --> 08:09.697
Rich people.
They would listen to you

08:09.697 --> 08:12.409
even if you were covered
in mud.

08:12.409 --> 08:15.329
Once, maybe. Not now.

08:16.413 --> 08:18.415
That's not
the Henry Gowen I know.

08:18.415 --> 08:21.709
The man I know
lives to make a deal,

08:21.709 --> 08:23.211
and if you could
pull this off,

08:23.211 --> 08:26.547
it would be the greatest deal
you ever made.

08:26.547 --> 08:28.300
Well, I can give it a shot,

08:28.300 --> 08:31.552
but you got to understand
it's a long shot.

08:32.679 --> 08:35.307
I'm not a gambler, Henry...

08:35.307 --> 08:38.143
but aren't long shots where
the big pay-offs are earned?

08:38.143 --> 08:41.188
[CHUCKLES]
You know, you may not
realize it, Abigail,

08:41.188 --> 08:44.607
but the moment you became Mayor,
you became a gambler.

08:44.607 --> 08:46.818
[♪♪♪]

08:58.121 --> 09:01.416
I'll bet Miss Thatcher
will make me usher.

09:01.416 --> 09:02.750
I'd be a good usher.

09:02.750 --> 09:05.420
I wanna be the one
who lights the candles.

09:05.420 --> 09:07.922
Do you think we're gonna
have to call Miss Thatcher

09:07.922 --> 09:09.757
"Mrs. Thornton"
when she gets back?

09:09.757 --> 09:11.592
If she comes back to school.

09:11.592 --> 09:13.178
ROBERT:
What do you mean, if?

09:13.178 --> 09:15.972
Don't you know what happens
when teachers get married?

09:18.141 --> 09:19.976
They have their own family.

09:19.976 --> 09:22.562
Miss Thatcher
won't have time to teach us.

09:22.562 --> 09:24.605
She'll be busy
with her own kids.

09:24.605 --> 09:26.733
Do you think
that's true?

09:27.734 --> 09:29.736
It happened
at my old school.

09:29.736 --> 09:32.989
The teacher got married.
We didn't see her again.

09:34.615 --> 09:38.412
ROBERT:
It won't be the same
without Miss Thatcher.

09:38.412 --> 09:40.621
[♪♪♪]

09:42.874 --> 09:44.543
Well, thanks
for joining me.

09:44.543 --> 09:45.752
Are you kidding?

09:45.752 --> 09:47.837
On horseback
in the countryside?

09:47.837 --> 09:49.423
What's better
than that?

09:49.423 --> 09:52.133
You can make even taking a run
for medical supplies

09:52.133 --> 09:54.635
sound romantic.
Because it can be.

09:54.635 --> 09:56.721
[LAUGHS]

09:57.847 --> 10:00.434
I can see
the appeal of this place.

10:00.434 --> 10:03.061
Could you see yourself
pursuing your career here?

10:03.061 --> 10:06.314
Every town needs homes, shops.

10:06.314 --> 10:09.484
But nothing that fully
utilizes your talent.

10:09.484 --> 10:14.155
Architecture is all about
seeing possibilities.

10:14.155 --> 10:16.699
Maybe I see something here.

10:16.699 --> 10:20.745
[CHUCKLES]
I love the way
you look at things.

10:20.745 --> 10:23.623
And I bet you that translates
into your designs.

10:23.623 --> 10:26.376
Until someone hires me
to design a building,

10:26.376 --> 10:28.628
you may never know.

10:29.796 --> 10:31.798
Ah, something'll
come through for you.

10:31.798 --> 10:34.717
That's kind of you to say,
but...

10:34.717 --> 10:37.304
nothing has,
and it's been over a year.

10:37.304 --> 10:40.765
Well, life has a way
of changing in an instant.

10:46.062 --> 10:47.606
Oh...

10:47.606 --> 10:51.651
[GASPS]
Rosemary, you have
really outdone yourself.

10:51.651 --> 10:54.154
I've never had so much fun
designing a dress before.

10:54.154 --> 10:56.781
Elizabeth might want
something a little simpler.

10:56.781 --> 10:59.033
Oh! She may think
that's what she wants,

10:59.033 --> 11:01.578
but this is
her day to shine.

11:01.578 --> 11:03.413
[ALL SIGHING DREAMILY]

11:05.248 --> 11:07.041
Hi!

11:07.041 --> 11:08.668
Thank you.

11:08.668 --> 11:10.211
Sorry I'm late.

11:10.211 --> 11:12.422
[♪♪♪]

11:14.715 --> 11:16.468
[GASPING]

11:16.468 --> 11:19.471
Oh, Rosemary, it's beautiful.

11:19.471 --> 11:21.556
I just knew
you would love it!

11:21.556 --> 11:27.312
I do! It's just so...much.
I know!

11:27.312 --> 11:30.231
I'm going to Benson Hills
to pick up the fabric tomorrow.

11:30.231 --> 11:32.442
I'm not sure I have
that kind of money on hand.

11:32.442 --> 11:34.693
Now, don't you worry.
I will get it on credit

11:34.693 --> 11:37.030
and you can pay me later.
I'll pay the supplier

11:37.030 --> 11:39.366
when Abigail gets
this bank issue sorted out.

11:39.366 --> 11:41.618
Or we could go with
a less expensive fabric,

11:41.618 --> 11:43.244
and perhaps
not as much of it.

11:43.244 --> 11:45.539
Elizabeth...

11:45.539 --> 11:47.374
[PAPER RUSTLES]

11:47.374 --> 11:49.626
This is your day.

11:49.626 --> 11:52.671
I refuse to let you
compromise.

11:52.671 --> 11:54.673
Clara?

11:54.673 --> 11:55.840
Come.

12:01.638 --> 12:05.225
Look at how lovely
you look.

12:06.267 --> 12:07.935
I'm gonna make sure
your wedding

12:07.935 --> 12:10.689
is everything
you ever dreamed of.

12:10.689 --> 12:12.773
And more.

12:12.773 --> 12:14.901
[♪♪♪]

12:14.901 --> 12:16.403
[CHUCKLES]

12:25.870 --> 12:28.373
You want my blessing?

12:28.373 --> 12:29.999
That usually comes before

12:29.999 --> 12:32.460
asking a man's daughter
for her hand in marriage.

12:32.460 --> 12:35.422
When I proposed, I was heading
into the Northern Territories

12:35.422 --> 12:38.007
and there wasn't time
to do it the traditional way.

12:38.007 --> 12:40.260
I want to do this
right, sir.

12:40.260 --> 12:42.011
Elizabeth wrote
to her mother and me

12:42.011 --> 12:44.556
about what was
going on up there.

12:44.556 --> 12:46.057
How did you--

12:46.057 --> 12:47.684
How is Mrs. Thatcher?

12:48.643 --> 12:50.228
Well, she's in London,

12:50.228 --> 12:52.397
caring for Viola
and her new baby.

12:52.397 --> 12:55.316
It's...probably
not a good time

12:55.316 --> 12:56.859
for Elizabeth to get married.

12:56.859 --> 12:58.653
Well, it may never
be a good time,

12:58.653 --> 13:00.655
but it is the right time.

13:00.655 --> 13:05.285
Will you two marry
even if I withhold my blessing?

13:05.285 --> 13:07.495
Yes, sir, we will.

13:07.495 --> 13:09.414
Ah.

13:09.414 --> 13:12.959
Then...why are we even
having this conversation?

13:12.959 --> 13:15.128
Because your approval,
it means a lot.

13:15.128 --> 13:17.880
Apparently, not enough.

13:21.050 --> 13:24.345
I wouldn't be here
if it didn't matter, sir.

13:24.345 --> 13:25.972
I want you to know,
Constable,

13:25.972 --> 13:27.932
that I have never
disapproved of you.

13:27.932 --> 13:29.517
On the contrary,

13:29.517 --> 13:31.436
I have high respect
for your character,

13:31.436 --> 13:34.355
your honesty,
and your devotion to duty.

13:35.607 --> 13:37.651
My question has always been,

13:37.651 --> 13:40.111
are you the right match
for Elizabeth?

13:40.111 --> 13:42.530
Given your far
different backgrounds.

13:42.530 --> 13:43.990
With all due respect, sir,

13:43.990 --> 13:47.577
marriage isn't about the past,
it's about the future.

13:47.577 --> 13:50.079
Elizabeth and I,
we love each other.

13:50.079 --> 13:51.539
We're going to have a family.

13:51.539 --> 13:54.626
These will be
your grandchildren.

13:54.626 --> 13:57.878
Soon, you'll be bouncing
them on your knee.

13:57.878 --> 13:59.838
It's in everyone's
best interest

13:59.838 --> 14:02.133
to get this marriage
off to a good start.

14:03.968 --> 14:06.346
Mr. Thatcher,
I know

14:06.346 --> 14:08.765
you want
what's best for Elizabeth.

14:08.765 --> 14:11.142
So do I.

14:11.142 --> 14:13.520
I promise you...

14:13.520 --> 14:17.398
I will devote my life
to making her happy.

14:27.074 --> 14:29.285
[♪♪♪]

14:32.747 --> 14:36.209
Oh, I loved those biscuits
from yesterday.

14:40.129 --> 14:42.089
So how are things
going with the bank?

14:42.089 --> 14:44.425
I'm working on getting
private investors.

14:44.425 --> 14:47.011
So how are things
going with your dress?

14:47.011 --> 14:48.471
Good.

14:48.471 --> 14:50.097
Just good?

14:50.097 --> 14:52.642
The dress will
be beautiful.

14:52.642 --> 14:53.852
I just feel like

14:53.852 --> 14:55.812
I don't really have
much of a say in it.

14:55.812 --> 14:58.189
Well, if you want
to get Rosemary to listen,

14:58.189 --> 14:59.691
you have to get
her attention.

14:59.691 --> 15:02.485
That's easier said than done.
Well, let's talk about

15:02.485 --> 15:05.613
something that only you and Jack
can plan-- your honeymoon.

15:05.613 --> 15:08.282
ELIZABETH:
We're planning on leaving
a few days after the wedding.

15:08.282 --> 15:10.243
Where are you going?
Chicago.

15:10.243 --> 15:12.662
Oh, I hear
Chicago is beautiful.

15:12.662 --> 15:14.455
I think Jack's
really gonna like it.

15:14.455 --> 15:17.876
They've got great theater,
museums, a new baseball stadium.

15:17.876 --> 15:19.960
I am so happy for you two.

15:19.960 --> 15:21.755
Oh, you're gonna have
the best time.

15:21.755 --> 15:23.590
We're really excited.

15:23.590 --> 15:25.800
Oh, speak of the devil.

15:25.800 --> 15:28.469
[♪♪♪]

15:31.097 --> 15:33.725
Ladies.
Welcome back!

15:33.725 --> 15:37.228
Thanks. Uh...
Care to join me for a ride?

15:37.228 --> 15:39.021
Can't wait to hear
about your trip.

15:39.021 --> 15:40.815
That's definitely
on the agenda.

15:40.815 --> 15:43.150
We'll finish
this conversation later.

15:43.150 --> 15:44.569
Have fun.

15:46.696 --> 15:48.907
[♪♪♪]

15:51.618 --> 15:52.827
Ooh!

16:03.212 --> 16:05.172
It's not just us,
Abigail.

16:05.172 --> 16:07.467
All the merchants
in town are suffering.

16:07.467 --> 16:09.343
I'm in the same boat as you.

16:09.343 --> 16:12.430
That's why I have a proposal
for every merchant in town.

16:12.430 --> 16:15.266
We should start extending
credit to our customers.

16:15.266 --> 16:18.478
Well, I would
love to, Abigail,

16:18.478 --> 16:20.897
but I don't know when the bank
is going to open,

16:20.897 --> 16:22.356
or even if it's going to.

16:22.356 --> 16:24.525
How can I be sure
I will be paid?

16:24.525 --> 16:26.444
Because every cent
of credit extended

16:26.444 --> 16:28.195
will be backed
by Hope Valley.

16:28.195 --> 16:30.490
If the bank is closed,
how would that work?

16:30.490 --> 16:32.325
The town owns
a good amount of land.

16:32.325 --> 16:35.411
If need be, I'll sell it to pay
off the debt we accumulate.

16:36.579 --> 16:39.624
Well, I can't speak
for everyone else,

16:39.624 --> 16:42.919
but your word
is good enough for me.

16:42.919 --> 16:45.797
The mercantile will
start extending credit today.

16:45.797 --> 16:47.423
Thank you.

16:47.423 --> 16:49.342
Thank you very much.

16:54.639 --> 16:56.975
[EXHALES]

16:58.309 --> 17:03.105
So are you gonna tell me
about this surprise?

17:03.105 --> 17:06.317
I went to get
your father's blessing.

17:06.317 --> 17:08.444
What did he say?

17:08.444 --> 17:09.904
He gave it to me.

17:09.904 --> 17:13.073
Oh, ho! Jack!
That's wonderful.

17:13.073 --> 17:14.701
But even if he said no,

17:14.701 --> 17:16.870
that would never
have stopped me.

17:16.870 --> 17:19.497
Me neither.

17:19.497 --> 17:22.249
This gets us off
on the right foot.

17:23.334 --> 17:25.336
Almost.

17:25.336 --> 17:27.881
What do you mean, almost?

17:29.089 --> 17:31.217
The Northern Territories.

17:32.343 --> 17:34.220
What about it?

17:34.220 --> 17:35.722
Exactly.

17:35.722 --> 17:37.682
Since you've been back,
it feels like

17:37.682 --> 17:39.934
you haven't talked about it.
It seems like

17:39.934 --> 17:41.644
you've been
avoiding the subject.

17:41.644 --> 17:43.396
That's because
it's behind me.

17:43.396 --> 17:45.857
No, it's a part of you,
and it always will be.

17:45.857 --> 17:48.108
You don't want
to hear about it, Elizabeth.

17:48.108 --> 17:50.611
But I want to.

17:50.611 --> 17:52.739
Jack, we're a couple,

17:52.739 --> 17:56.116
and successful couples share
everything with each other.

17:56.116 --> 17:58.745
I need to know
you're on board with that.

17:59.704 --> 18:01.330
[HOOVES CLOPPING]

18:01.330 --> 18:03.917
Glad I found you two.

18:03.917 --> 18:05.585
ELIZABETH:
Is something wrong?

18:05.585 --> 18:07.921
There will be,
if Rosemary doesn't get her way.

18:07.921 --> 18:11.632
She needs you both
to come to the café right now.

18:11.632 --> 18:13.843
[♪♪♪]

18:16.554 --> 18:18.472
LEE:
I'll let you know
soon, Henry.

18:18.472 --> 18:19.849
Well,
I appreciate it.

18:19.849 --> 18:21.559
I'm just looking
for a fair shot.

18:21.559 --> 18:23.143
Mm-hmm.

18:27.481 --> 18:29.149
Hey, Jesse.

18:29.149 --> 18:31.778
Can I talk to you for a minute?
Yes, sir.

18:31.778 --> 18:34.488
I need a new man
on one of the logging crews,

18:34.488 --> 18:37.617
and, uh...
Gowen asked for the job.

18:37.617 --> 18:40.954
Sure. It pays a lot more
than what he's doing right now.

18:40.954 --> 18:42.830
Yeah.
You supervise him.

18:42.830 --> 18:44.164
What do you think?

18:46.417 --> 18:48.377
Honestly?

18:48.377 --> 18:50.546
Yes. Honesty would be best.

18:50.546 --> 18:53.340
Working on a logging crew's
really hard work.

18:53.340 --> 18:55.259
Takes a certain
kind of man to do it.

18:55.259 --> 18:57.887
And even though Mr. Gowen's
doing his job okay,

18:57.887 --> 19:00.264
I think maybe
he spent a little too much

19:00.264 --> 19:02.141
of his life
behind a desk.

19:02.141 --> 19:03.476
Maybe.

19:03.476 --> 19:05.478
There's plenty of guys
who've been working

19:05.478 --> 19:07.229
longer that could use
the extra pay.

19:07.229 --> 19:08.898
Right.
Thanks for your thoughts.

19:08.898 --> 19:11.317
I got to get back to town.
See you later.

19:18.282 --> 19:19.826
Florence and Dottie,

19:19.826 --> 19:22.286
how are we doing with
the floral arrangements?

19:22.286 --> 19:24.497
We need volunteers
to donate flowers

19:24.497 --> 19:26.540
and bring them
to the church.

19:26.540 --> 19:29.752
And we thought the children
could gather wildflowers.

19:29.752 --> 19:31.253
Oh! Good idea.

19:31.253 --> 19:33.213
Cody can organize
his friends to help.

19:33.213 --> 19:34.381
Here we are.

19:34.381 --> 19:35.675
And now, best men.

19:35.675 --> 19:38.177
Do you know
where the rings are?

19:38.177 --> 19:40.179
Do you?
I don't know
where the rings are.

19:40.179 --> 19:42.389
The rings?
I have the rings.

19:42.389 --> 19:45.267
ROSEMARY:
There you are!
Come, come, come!

19:48.062 --> 19:49.897
JACK:
Guard these carefully.

19:49.897 --> 19:51.691
With my life,
buddy.

19:51.691 --> 19:53.901
ROSEMARY:
We were just
discussing flowers.

19:53.901 --> 19:55.695
What would you like
for your bouquet?

19:55.695 --> 19:58.238
Uh, oh! Well,
I've always loved roses.

19:58.238 --> 20:00.658
They're not at
their best right now.

20:00.658 --> 20:02.910
How about...dahlias?

20:02.910 --> 20:05.038
Do we have to decide
this right now?

20:05.038 --> 20:07.915
We are completely jam-packed
from now until the wedding.

20:07.915 --> 20:10.209
We still have to plan
the bachelor's lunch. Lee?

20:10.209 --> 20:12.628
Oh, and there's
the girls' bridal tea.

20:12.628 --> 20:14.213
ELIZABETH:
That sounds lovely,

20:14.213 --> 20:16.298
but you all doing so much,
and, really,

20:16.298 --> 20:18.551
Jack and I would like
to keep things simple.

20:18.551 --> 20:21.095
ROSEMARY [LAUGHS]:
You say that now!

20:21.095 --> 20:23.097
It is our job
to make sure

20:23.097 --> 20:25.265
your wedding
is as special

20:25.265 --> 20:27.727
and as wonderful
as you are.

20:30.980 --> 20:33.107
Wonderful.

20:36.944 --> 20:40.907
[♪♪♪]

20:40.907 --> 20:42.282
Hey, Katie.

20:44.284 --> 20:46.913
Hi, Dr. Shepherd.
Cash or credit?

20:46.913 --> 20:49.165
I still happen
to have a little cash.

20:49.165 --> 20:50.708
You're one of the few.

20:50.708 --> 20:53.586
Oh, a telegram came for you
from San Francisco.

20:53.586 --> 20:54.879
Okay. Great.

20:54.879 --> 20:56.839
Rosemary's more excited
about the wedding

20:56.839 --> 20:59.050
than you and Jack are.
I know she means well,

20:59.050 --> 21:01.427
I wish I could ask her
to take a step back.

21:01.427 --> 21:03.054
A baby step.
Or 10.

21:03.054 --> 21:05.806
Hey, ladies.
Hey.
Hi, Carson.

21:05.806 --> 21:07.767
I'm looking forward to Jack's
bachelor luncheon.

21:07.767 --> 21:10.061
Great!
KATIE:
Here it is.

21:10.061 --> 21:11.562
Thank you.
Mm-hm.

21:11.562 --> 21:13.856
ELIZABETH:
I wish I had
a moment to breathe.

21:13.856 --> 21:15.900
It feels like Rosemary
is scheduling

21:15.900 --> 21:19.486
every minute of every day
with something wedding-related,

21:19.486 --> 21:21.030
whether it's
a dress fitting,

21:21.030 --> 21:23.365
or picking out the centerpieces
for the tables,

21:23.365 --> 21:25.785
or the napkins
for the dinner or--

21:25.785 --> 21:26.953
Oh! That reminds me--

21:26.953 --> 21:28.662
we have to finalize
the menu.

21:28.662 --> 21:30.372
Of course.
Talk to Rosemary.

21:30.372 --> 21:32.792
See if she can
schedule it.

21:32.792 --> 21:34.376
Elizabeth,

21:34.376 --> 21:37.004
we love you
and Jack so much.

21:37.004 --> 21:38.464
We want what's
best for you.

21:38.464 --> 21:39.757
I know.

21:39.757 --> 21:41.759
In a week, you will be
blissfully married

21:41.759 --> 21:43.844
and you will forget everything
you had to go through

21:43.844 --> 21:45.387
to get to that
precious moment.

21:45.387 --> 21:48.474
I'm going to go look
for some bubble bath.

21:48.474 --> 21:49.725
Maybe that'll relax me.

21:50.851 --> 21:52.770
Let's hope.

21:53.896 --> 21:56.149
[EXHALES DEEPLY]
Oh.

21:56.983 --> 21:59.193
[♪♪♪]

22:01.654 --> 22:04.782
HENRY:
I know what you did.

22:04.782 --> 22:06.325
What are you talking about?

22:06.325 --> 22:08.410
Blocking my promotion.

22:08.410 --> 22:11.455
That was
Mr. Coulter's decision.

22:11.455 --> 22:13.540
With your input.

22:13.540 --> 22:15.501
JESSE:
Fact is, Mr. Gowen,

22:15.501 --> 22:17.170
you weren't
the best choice.

22:17.170 --> 22:18.796
The man who is
got the job.

22:18.796 --> 22:20.339
It was nothing
personal.

22:20.339 --> 22:21.590
Oh, I don't
believe that.

22:21.590 --> 22:23.301
JESSE:
Believe whatever you want.

22:23.301 --> 22:25.136
Does it make
you feel good?

22:25.136 --> 22:26.846
Seeing me brought down?

22:26.846 --> 22:28.264
You feel like
a big man?

22:28.264 --> 22:29.556
CLARA:
That's enough!

22:29.556 --> 22:32.143
Henry Gowen...

22:32.143 --> 22:33.269
[SCOFFS]

22:33.269 --> 22:35.479
How dare you make
such accusations?

22:35.479 --> 22:37.940
You haven't been
treated unfairly at all.

22:37.940 --> 22:41.068
Mrs. Stanton,
this doesn't concern you.

22:41.068 --> 22:43.612
Oh, if it concerns Jesse,
it concerns me.

22:43.612 --> 22:45.823
I know how hard he works
at that sawmill,

22:45.823 --> 22:47.741
and I know
how much respect he has

22:47.741 --> 22:49.451
for all of his co-workers.

22:49.451 --> 22:52.121
If you believe that
you've been treated unfairly,

22:52.121 --> 22:53.789
take it up with Lee Coulter,

22:53.789 --> 22:56.209
but leave Jesse out of it.

22:56.209 --> 23:00.129
He is a far better man
than you will ever be.

23:02.464 --> 23:04.675
[♪♪♪]

23:15.769 --> 23:19.065
SOFIA:
There's something
so peaceful here...

23:19.065 --> 23:20.816
and of course,
it's special,

23:20.816 --> 23:23.027
because it's where
we had our first date.

23:23.027 --> 23:26.488
This place will always
bring great memories.

23:26.488 --> 23:29.407
That almost sounds
like a goodbye.

23:35.497 --> 23:36.916
What's that?

23:36.916 --> 23:39.335
It's a job offer.

23:39.335 --> 23:40.586
For?

23:40.586 --> 23:42.129
For you.

23:42.129 --> 23:43.881
In San Francisco.

23:43.881 --> 23:46.342
I don't understand.

23:47.634 --> 23:49.803
I have an old friend
who works with the mayor

23:49.803 --> 23:52.723
at the city planning office.
They want to hire me.

23:52.723 --> 23:54.100
The city's
still rebuilding

23:54.100 --> 23:56.352
after its big earthquake,
and it's expanding--

23:56.352 --> 23:58.687
more people, more jobs,
more roads...

23:58.687 --> 24:01.565
This is a dream job.

24:01.565 --> 24:04.610
High-rises, theaters,
Victorian row houses,

24:04.610 --> 24:06.028
Queen Anne homes...

24:06.028 --> 24:07.821
the list is endless.

24:07.821 --> 24:10.699
Carson...

24:10.699 --> 24:13.535
thank you.

24:17.331 --> 24:19.375
You're an amazing man.

24:19.375 --> 24:21.585
I'm gonna miss you.

24:21.585 --> 24:23.129
You kidding me?

24:23.129 --> 24:25.172
You've given me
the perfect excuse

24:25.172 --> 24:26.966
to come visit San Francisco.

24:26.966 --> 24:29.885
You'll be welcome any time.

24:32.054 --> 24:33.931
Come on.

24:38.644 --> 24:40.771
[KNOCKING]

24:46.652 --> 24:48.486
Jack.

24:50.448 --> 24:53.491
I need to talk
to you, Elizabeth.

24:53.491 --> 24:55.328
What's going on?

24:56.578 --> 24:59.706
What you said about
not sharing everything--

24:59.706 --> 25:02.668
you were right.

25:02.668 --> 25:04.586
I'm sorry.

25:05.671 --> 25:07.798
Thank you, Jack.

25:14.096 --> 25:15.889
I have to warn you, though,

25:15.889 --> 25:19.018
what happened up there,
it wasn't always pretty.

25:20.727 --> 25:23.356
Life isn't
always pretty,

25:23.356 --> 25:25.024
but being married

25:25.024 --> 25:28.568
is about sharing
the good and the bad.

25:29.695 --> 25:31.905
[♪♪♪]

25:44.418 --> 25:46.086
We had taken losses before,

25:46.086 --> 25:48.422
but nothing like this,
Elizabeth.

25:49.465 --> 25:51.509
One day,
we were out on patrol

25:51.509 --> 25:54.220
and my squad was ambushed.

25:54.220 --> 25:58.224
When the shooting stopped,
I thought we were all okay...

25:59.850 --> 26:02.395
But this new recruit was hit.

26:02.395 --> 26:04.562
He didn't make it.

26:09.276 --> 26:11.904
The night before,

26:11.904 --> 26:15.199
he came up to me and he told me
that he was scared,

26:15.199 --> 26:18.160
and I assured him
that he'd be okay.

26:18.160 --> 26:20.954
[CHUCKLES SADLY]
I even put him at the back

26:20.954 --> 26:23.541
because I thought
he'd be safer there.

26:24.833 --> 26:26.877
He wasn't.

26:29.755 --> 26:31.465
Jack...

26:34.134 --> 26:37.096
That was not your fault.

26:38.389 --> 26:41.850
It's just, um...

26:41.850 --> 26:44.478
it's hard to stop
thinking about it.

26:47.189 --> 26:49.358
I know.

26:49.358 --> 26:52.111
It must be very hard.

26:54.905 --> 26:57.533
Thank you
for telling me.

26:59.785 --> 27:02.079
Thanks for being you.

27:12.548 --> 27:14.508
JACK:
Is it just me,

27:14.508 --> 27:18.178
or is this wedding becoming
more than it should be?

27:18.178 --> 27:20.847
[LAUGHS]
I know they all mean well.

27:20.847 --> 27:22.600
Hello, Philip!

27:22.600 --> 27:24.893
Hi.
ELIZABETH:
I was just telling Mountie Jack

27:24.893 --> 27:26.604
you agreed
to be our ring bearer.

27:26.604 --> 27:27.896
He's happy
you took the job.

27:27.896 --> 27:29.773
I can't imagine
anyone I'd trust more

27:29.773 --> 27:31.984
with those rings.

27:31.984 --> 27:33.986
Is something
wrong, Philip?

27:33.986 --> 27:36.405
No. I should be
going home now.

27:36.405 --> 27:39.866
ELIZABETH:
Oh. All right.

27:39.866 --> 27:41.743
What do you think
that was about?

27:41.743 --> 27:44.037
I don't know.

27:49.502 --> 27:52.421
Well...I'm here.

27:52.421 --> 27:53.464
Are you ready?

27:53.464 --> 27:54.548
Yeah.

27:54.548 --> 27:56.467
Yeah, as ready
as I'll ever be.

27:56.467 --> 27:59.094
Have fun.
You too.

28:02.222 --> 28:04.141
Enjoy, Jack!

28:04.141 --> 28:05.518
Thanks, Bill.

28:05.518 --> 28:07.478
There you go.

28:07.478 --> 28:09.146
Mm. Mm!

28:09.146 --> 28:11.398
So how's the house
planning coming?

28:11.398 --> 28:13.317
Oh, it's coming along.

28:13.317 --> 28:16.195
Listen. I am, uh, I'm
selling you the lumber,

28:16.195 --> 28:17.571
but I am
giving you my time.

28:17.571 --> 28:19.031
Weekends,
whatever it takes,

28:19.031 --> 28:20.324
I'm gonna help you build.

28:20.324 --> 28:21.908
I appreciate it, Lee.
Yeah.

28:22.826 --> 28:25.078
Okay. That is hot.

28:25.078 --> 28:26.372
Whoo!

28:26.372 --> 28:28.415
It's good for you.
Clears out your sinuses.

28:28.415 --> 28:30.209
Bill, I have
missed your chili.

28:30.209 --> 28:32.044
If you're stuck
for a wedding gift,

28:32.044 --> 28:34.338
I want you to teach
Elizabeth how to make it.

28:34.338 --> 28:37.799
You asking me to give up
my secret family recipe?

28:37.799 --> 28:39.593
Uh...

28:39.593 --> 28:41.928
Well, consider it done.
Elizabeth is family.

28:41.928 --> 28:43.389
So what does that
make you?

28:43.389 --> 28:44.640
The black sheep?

28:44.640 --> 28:46.308
[MEN CHUCKLING]

28:48.686 --> 28:50.312
Henry.

28:50.312 --> 28:52.398
The saloon's closed.
It's a private party.

28:52.398 --> 28:54.233
JACK:
Bill.

28:54.233 --> 28:55.817
Didn't invite him?

28:55.817 --> 28:57.277
Should I have?

28:59.279 --> 29:01.240
Henry...

29:01.240 --> 29:03.409
Join us. Please.

29:03.409 --> 29:05.952
I don't think
I'm wanted here, Jack.

29:05.952 --> 29:07.954
I want you here.

29:09.456 --> 29:11.667
[♪♪♪]

29:17.590 --> 29:19.132
Thank you.

29:20.384 --> 29:22.219
JACK:
You're welcome.

29:22.219 --> 29:23.220
Congratulations.

29:23.220 --> 29:24.804
Thank you.

29:27.641 --> 29:29.851
You're looking at
the current darts champion

29:29.851 --> 29:31.144
of Hope Valley,

29:31.144 --> 29:33.813
unless you think
you can beat me.

29:33.813 --> 29:36.483
Prepare to lose your crown,
young man.

29:36.483 --> 29:39.236
Okay.

29:39.236 --> 29:41.280
I didn't know how
you felt about him.

29:42.322 --> 29:44.533
Henry's part of the community.

29:44.533 --> 29:45.867
Hey there, folks.

29:45.867 --> 29:48.328
Mind if I borrow
the groom for a minute?

29:49.496 --> 29:51.373
Listen, I hate
to spring this on you,

29:51.373 --> 29:53.542
but Rosemary's kinda
been on me about this.

29:53.542 --> 29:55.461
Um...

29:56.629 --> 29:58.088
What are they?

29:58.088 --> 29:59.632
Color schemes
for the wedding.

29:59.632 --> 30:00.924
Color schemes for the we--

30:00.924 --> 30:02.593
I didn't know
weddings had color schemes.

30:02.593 --> 30:04.678
Well, it'll affect
which suit you wear.

30:04.678 --> 30:06.555
I'm not wearing a suit.
I'm a Mountie.

30:06.555 --> 30:08.348
I'm gonna get married
in my uniform.

30:08.348 --> 30:10.809
Does Elizabeth know
that's what you want to wear?

30:10.809 --> 30:12.561
We haven't even
talked about it.

30:12.561 --> 30:14.146
[WHISTLES]
Hmm.

30:14.146 --> 30:15.606
You might want
to tell her.

30:15.606 --> 30:16.940
Soon.

30:16.940 --> 30:18.734
Color schemes.
Important.

30:18.734 --> 30:20.152
Okay, everybody, listen up!

30:20.152 --> 30:21.903
It's that time of the party

30:21.903 --> 30:24.323
where we all have
to make a toast to the groom.

30:24.323 --> 30:25.407
Bill--
[MEN GRUMBLE]

30:25.407 --> 30:26.492
No, come on.

30:26.492 --> 30:29.035
Those are the rules.

30:29.035 --> 30:31.121
To Jack Thornton...

30:31.121 --> 30:33.707
a man who found
the perfect woman...

30:33.707 --> 30:35.917
and took forever
to do something about it.

30:35.917 --> 30:38.170
[ALL LAUGH]

30:38.170 --> 30:39.963
"Love is patient"--
luckily for you.

30:39.963 --> 30:41.381
Congrats, Jack.
ALL: Cheers!

30:41.381 --> 30:42.633
Jack!
MAN: To Jack!

30:42.633 --> 30:44.426
Thanks, everyone. Cheers!

30:44.426 --> 30:45.969
[WOMAN LAUGHING]

30:45.969 --> 30:48.681
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

30:57.272 --> 30:58.898
ROSEMARY:
Now, Elizabeth,

30:58.898 --> 31:01.694
as you know,
a bridal luncheon

31:01.694 --> 31:04.446
wouldn't be complete without
the time-honored tradition

31:04.446 --> 31:06.365
of "something old,
something new,

31:06.365 --> 31:08.283
something borrowed,
and something blue."

31:08.283 --> 31:12.245
Or, as I like to call them,
little tokens of love.

31:12.245 --> 31:13.831
I call them
good luck charms.

31:13.831 --> 31:15.290
Mm-hmm.

31:15.290 --> 31:18.084
Yeah. True.
WOMAN: Me too.

31:18.084 --> 31:21.505
Semantics have no place
at a bridal luncheon, ladies,

31:21.505 --> 31:22.798
but gifts do,

31:22.798 --> 31:24.466
and this one's from me.

31:24.466 --> 31:25.967
It's something old,

31:25.967 --> 31:28.804
and it represents
continuity in your life.

31:28.804 --> 31:31.139
Thank you, Rosemary.

31:31.139 --> 31:33.016
Oh...

31:33.016 --> 31:34.810
It's gorgeous.

31:36.729 --> 31:38.104
WOMAN:
It's beautiful.

31:38.104 --> 31:40.273
It was my grandmother's.

31:40.273 --> 31:42.651
I just know it'll look perfect
with your dress.

31:42.651 --> 31:45.945
Thank you so much.
I'm touched.

31:45.945 --> 31:48.073
CLARA:
And from me...

31:49.199 --> 31:50.950
Something new,

31:50.950 --> 31:52.578
which offers hope
for the future.

31:52.578 --> 31:54.538
Thank you, Clara.

31:54.538 --> 31:56.248
Oh!

31:56.248 --> 31:58.041
They're lovely!

31:58.041 --> 31:59.918
CLARA:
I made them myself.

31:59.918 --> 32:02.254
And even the box
I put them in is new.

32:02.254 --> 32:06.132
Oh! Well, thank you.
I will cherish them always.

32:07.092 --> 32:09.177
And from me...

32:09.177 --> 32:11.263
something borrowed.

32:16.518 --> 32:17.936
Abigail...

32:17.936 --> 32:20.689
they are stunning.

32:20.689 --> 32:22.566
[WOMEN GUSHING]

32:22.566 --> 32:24.777
Cultured pearls...

32:24.777 --> 32:26.862
which I wore at my wedding,

32:26.862 --> 32:28.864
which symbolizes
the happiness

32:28.864 --> 32:32.743
I know you and Jack will share
for the rest of your lives.

32:32.743 --> 32:35.370
Thank you so much.

32:35.370 --> 32:37.456
It means the world to me.

32:37.456 --> 32:40.793
But they're borrowed,
so you have to give them back.

32:40.793 --> 32:42.878
[ALL LAUGH]

32:45.088 --> 32:47.382
And now
for something blue...

32:49.301 --> 32:51.136
[♪♪♪]

32:51.136 --> 32:53.138
ROSEMARY:
Uh...

32:54.347 --> 32:57.058
We will surprise you
with that later...

32:57.058 --> 33:01.313
but, tomorrow, we need
to pick out champagne flutes.

33:01.313 --> 33:03.482
Rosemary, I was hoping that,
tomorrow,

33:03.482 --> 33:06.025
Jack and I might spend
a bit of time together.

33:06.025 --> 33:08.946
Oh, Elizabeth--
There is no time for time

33:08.946 --> 33:11.323
before the wedding!
There is so much to do,

33:11.323 --> 33:13.575
I can't even keep
my head straight!

33:13.575 --> 33:15.410
[WOMEN LAUGHING]

33:20.123 --> 33:22.793
Now, Elizabeth,
don't forget--

33:22.793 --> 33:25.086
tomorrow, we're doing
your dress measurements,

33:25.086 --> 33:26.630
so eat a light dinner.

33:26.630 --> 33:27.756
Will do.

33:27.756 --> 33:28.841
Elizabeth!

33:28.841 --> 33:31.301
Which do you prefer?

33:31.301 --> 33:33.637
Marigolds...or daisies?

33:33.637 --> 33:35.430
Daisies represent
cheerfulness

33:35.430 --> 33:36.890
and innocence.

33:36.890 --> 33:40.853
Well, marigolds represent
passion and creativity.

33:42.980 --> 33:44.690
I like them both.

33:44.690 --> 33:46.900
She likes them both.
Both? Well,

33:46.900 --> 33:49.027
marigolds and daisies
do not go together.

33:49.027 --> 33:51.154
Let's talk about colors.
I suggest yellow.

33:51.154 --> 33:53.573
I guess I better
start working on my speech

33:53.573 --> 33:54.783
for the reception dinner.

33:54.783 --> 33:55.826
I already wrote mine.

33:55.826 --> 33:57.160
Really?
Uh-huh.

33:57.160 --> 33:58.453
What are
you gonna say?

33:58.453 --> 34:00.455
I'm not gonna tell you
in front of Jack.

34:00.455 --> 34:02.457
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

34:02.457 --> 34:05.043
That's okay.
I think I'm needed anyway.

34:06.211 --> 34:08.672
Shall we?
What are you gonna say?

34:08.672 --> 34:12.300
WOMAN:
Well, marigolds are clearly
a more cheerful flower,

34:12.300 --> 34:14.427
and that represents
Elizabeth's personality.

34:14.427 --> 34:17.848
Excuse me, ladies. I'm gonna
borrow Elizabeth for a moment.

34:17.848 --> 34:20.475
Oh!
Thank you.

34:22.227 --> 34:24.396
Thank you
for rescuing me.

34:24.396 --> 34:26.147
What were they
arguing about?

34:26.147 --> 34:27.733
Flowers,
believe it or not.

34:27.733 --> 34:31.028
Flowers?
How was
your bachelor luncheon?

34:31.028 --> 34:32.278
It was good,
and yours?

34:32.278 --> 34:33.405
It was lovely.

34:33.405 --> 34:35.866
Good.

34:35.866 --> 34:37.784
But, Jack...

34:37.784 --> 34:40.662
this isn't how I imagined
our wedding.

34:40.662 --> 34:42.080
Friends are bickering.

34:42.080 --> 34:44.249
People are spending money
they don't have.

34:44.249 --> 34:45.876
There must be an easier way.

34:45.876 --> 34:47.753
There is...

34:47.753 --> 34:49.004
Eloping?

34:49.004 --> 34:50.923
Why not?
We'll throw a big party

34:50.923 --> 34:52.883
for everyone when we come back.

34:52.883 --> 34:55.677
I just-- I just want
to be married to you.

34:57.345 --> 34:58.972
Let's do it.

34:58.972 --> 35:00.098
Really?

35:01.558 --> 35:04.895
Okay, meet me at the livery
in an hour.

35:04.895 --> 35:07.439
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

35:07.439 --> 35:09.649
[♪♪♪]

35:17.156 --> 35:19.284
[♪♪♪]

35:19.284 --> 35:20.953
[CHUCKLES]

35:30.629 --> 35:32.798
Jesse--
Clara.

35:32.798 --> 35:34.215
[BOTH LAUGH]

35:36.635 --> 35:39.096
How was Jack's party?

35:39.096 --> 35:41.014
It was great.
And Elizabeth's?

35:41.014 --> 35:42.015
Fun.

35:42.015 --> 35:44.517
She looks so happy.

35:44.517 --> 35:46.603
And a little stressed.

35:46.603 --> 35:50.983
Hey...I wanted to thank you
for sticking up for me earlier.

35:50.983 --> 35:54.653
No one has ever
come to my defense that way.

35:54.653 --> 36:00.993
Well, maybe no one's ever
felt about you the way I do.

36:00.993 --> 36:02.995
You mean that?

36:02.995 --> 36:05.705
I do.

36:05.705 --> 36:09.084
Then, if you don't
mind me asking,

36:09.084 --> 36:11.753
what are we still doing
on a break?

36:11.753 --> 36:13.713
[LAUGHS]

36:13.713 --> 36:16.133
I've been thinking
the same thing.

36:17.134 --> 36:18.760
Are you saying...?

36:20.178 --> 36:22.806
I'm ready
to get back together.

36:23.849 --> 36:25.642
Me too.

36:27.060 --> 36:29.521
[♪♪♪]

36:38.321 --> 36:42.617
Oh, Sofia!
Spreading your wings!

36:42.617 --> 36:44.119
It's so exciting.

36:44.119 --> 36:45.745
The minute
you get some time off,

36:45.745 --> 36:47.873
you must come and visit me
in San Francisco.

36:47.873 --> 36:51.459
Absolutely. Just don't expect me
for months after the wedding.

36:51.459 --> 36:53.419
I'll need some time
to recover.

36:55.172 --> 36:57.382
[♪♪♪]

37:03.513 --> 37:05.891
Come on.

37:17.318 --> 37:20.155
You know what I still see
when I look in your eyes?

37:20.155 --> 37:22.032
[LAUGHS]
Potential.

37:22.032 --> 37:24.868
Big-time potential.

37:27.286 --> 37:30.040
[HORSE WHINNIES]

37:35.670 --> 37:37.839
It's a wonderful thing
you did for her.

37:37.839 --> 37:40.299
What's wonderful
is what she did for me.

37:40.299 --> 37:41.843
And what's that?

37:41.843 --> 37:45.346
She made me realize
I can open up my heart again.

37:48.850 --> 37:51.061
[♪♪♪]

37:55.440 --> 37:57.525
Hi.
Hi.

37:57.525 --> 38:00.028
Anyone see you?
Rosemary.

38:00.028 --> 38:02.447
She seemed a bit suspicious.
Yeah, Bill too.

38:02.447 --> 38:04.157
Better hurry
before word spreads.

38:04.157 --> 38:05.158
[BOTH LAUGHING]

38:05.158 --> 38:06.576
ABIGAIL:
Elizabeth!

38:06.576 --> 38:07.786
Abigail.

38:07.786 --> 38:09.495
Have either of you
seen Philip?

38:09.495 --> 38:11.456
Not recently, no.
Why?

38:11.456 --> 38:13.125
Mrs. Brayman
can't find him.

38:13.125 --> 38:14.918
He was supposed to be
at her house three hours ago.

38:14.918 --> 38:17.129
She's looked everywhere.
We saw him earlier.

38:17.129 --> 38:19.214
He seemed down.
Where would he run off to?

38:19.214 --> 38:21.133
I have an idea where
he might've gone.

38:21.133 --> 38:23.301
We'll need horses.
Stay here and look around.

38:23.301 --> 38:25.553
Think I know where to find him.
Okay.

38:25.553 --> 38:27.806
[SIGHS]

38:28.974 --> 38:31.184
[♪♪♪]

38:42.028 --> 38:44.656
[HOOVES CLOPPING]

38:44.656 --> 38:46.866
ELIZABETH:
Philip?

38:46.866 --> 38:49.286
Philip! Oh, my lord.

38:56.542 --> 38:58.795
Hi!

38:58.795 --> 39:00.588
What are you doing here?

39:00.588 --> 39:03.008
I wanted to be alone.

39:03.008 --> 39:05.010
Everyone was worried
about you, Philip.

39:05.010 --> 39:06.344
How'd you know I was here?

39:06.344 --> 39:07.637
Well, I remembered

39:07.637 --> 39:09.931
this is where you like
to look for tadpoles.

39:09.931 --> 39:11.599
Why do you want to be alone?

39:11.599 --> 39:13.143
I just do.

39:14.686 --> 39:17.438
Philip...

39:17.438 --> 39:20.317
You can tell me what's going on.
It's okay.

39:20.317 --> 39:22.694
JACK:
Believe me, Philip...

39:22.694 --> 39:24.445
talking helps.

39:26.823 --> 39:29.075
What's upsetting you?

39:30.660 --> 39:32.871
I'm mad at Mountie Jack.

39:34.580 --> 39:36.666
Why would you be mad
at Mountie Jack?

39:36.666 --> 39:38.293
He's taking you
away from us!

39:38.293 --> 39:39.627
What do you mean?

39:39.627 --> 39:41.213
I heard the other kids
talking,

39:41.213 --> 39:43.506
and they said,
once teachers get married,

39:43.506 --> 39:44.966
they have their own family,

39:44.966 --> 39:47.260
and they don't come
back to school anymore.

39:49.971 --> 39:52.182
[♪♪♪]

39:55.977 --> 39:58.563
What the other kids said...

39:58.563 --> 40:00.315
it's not true.

40:00.315 --> 40:01.941
You're staying
in Hope Valley?

40:01.941 --> 40:03.526
This is my home!

40:03.526 --> 40:05.611
Harper said it happened
to his last teacher.

40:05.611 --> 40:07.822
I'm sure it does happen
with some teachers,

40:07.822 --> 40:09.991
but the people
of Hope Valley

40:09.991 --> 40:11.784
are too special to me.

40:11.784 --> 40:13.452
I couldn't leave.

40:13.452 --> 40:15.872
This is where I belong,
same as you.

40:15.872 --> 40:17.832
No matter what happens,

40:17.832 --> 40:20.043
I'm staying
right where I am,

40:20.043 --> 40:21.294
and that's a promise.

40:21.294 --> 40:23.504
[♪♪♪]

40:28.176 --> 40:29.886
Thank you.

40:31.763 --> 40:33.139
[SIGHING]

40:33.139 --> 40:35.600
Jack...I've been thinking.

40:35.600 --> 40:36.726
I know.

40:36.726 --> 40:38.311
We can't elope.

40:38.311 --> 40:40.397
It isn't just Philip.

40:40.397 --> 40:41.856
You mean a lot
to this town.

40:41.856 --> 40:44.734
We do!
This town needs this wedding.

40:44.734 --> 40:46.986
But...it doesn't mean

40:46.986 --> 40:49.572
we can't do at least
a few things our way.

40:49.572 --> 40:51.657
Watch out, Hope Valley,

40:51.657 --> 40:53.910
the future Mrs. Thornton
is taking charge.

40:53.910 --> 40:55.578
[GIGGLES]

40:58.456 --> 41:01.626
We called you here because we
love each and every one of you.

41:01.626 --> 41:04.170
ELIZABETH:
We're glad you're
part of our wedding.

41:04.170 --> 41:06.423
However...it is our wedding.

41:06.423 --> 41:09.717
Our special day. Jack and I
should be in charge of it.

41:09.717 --> 41:11.010
JACK:
Don't get us wrong,

41:11.010 --> 41:13.388
we're grateful
for everyone's help.

41:13.388 --> 41:15.181
ELIZABETH:
When all's said and done,

41:15.181 --> 41:16.891
we need to make
our own decisions.

41:16.891 --> 41:18.310
We hope you'll understand.

41:18.310 --> 41:19.894
Of course
we understand.

41:19.894 --> 41:20.937
I'm glad
you spoke up.

41:20.937 --> 41:22.105
We just
want you guys

41:22.105 --> 41:23.689
to have everything
you want.

41:23.689 --> 41:25.483
And I suppose some of us

41:25.483 --> 41:28.694
have been a little
overenthusiastic.

41:28.694 --> 41:30.488
A "little"?

41:30.488 --> 41:31.823
[ALL CHUCKLING]

41:31.823 --> 41:33.866
Take the reins.
ELIZABETH: Thank you.

41:33.866 --> 41:35.785
Thank you all.

41:37.870 --> 41:40.539
[PEOPLE CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

41:42.500 --> 41:44.836
ROSEMARY:
All right,
everyone, you heard them.

41:44.836 --> 41:46.587
There is a lot of work to do.

41:46.587 --> 41:48.423
FLORENCE:
Not much time
to get it done!

41:48.423 --> 41:50.383
LEE:
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
To do what?

41:50.383 --> 41:53.303
Our color scheme
is completely wrong.

41:53.303 --> 41:56.055
If Jack wants to get married
in the red uniform--

41:56.055 --> 41:58.391
We'll have to design
a palette with warm tones.

41:58.391 --> 42:00.143
If it's gonna be
a Mountie wedding,

42:00.143 --> 42:01.978
we should have
a Mountie honor guard.

42:01.978 --> 42:04.439
I'll wire Jack's
commanding officer.

42:04.439 --> 42:07.859
Well...that lasted
about five seconds.

42:07.859 --> 42:09.110
[ALL LAUGHING]

42:09.110 --> 42:10.820
What are you
smiling at?

42:10.820 --> 42:13.281
We're a part of
a community that cares.

42:13.281 --> 42:15.950
Even if they care
a little too much.

42:15.950 --> 42:18.161
"A little."

42:18.161 --> 42:20.372
[♪♪♪]

42:24.792 --> 42:27.337
Mm. Oh, boy.

42:27.337 --> 42:29.047
[BOTH LAUGHING]

42:30.715 --> 42:32.925
[♪♪♪]
